76561198034420858,Recommended,249190,12255081,"Posted: 26 September, 2014",all,Tedimus Maximus,"If you love RTS, then you need to give this game a shot!I have played many RTS games and love ones that are space themed and this is the BEST one thus far.  I have played Sins of a Solar Empire, Galaxy Civ. and many others... Thank you for creating this!  Keep in mind that this is currently meant to be a single player game strategy only.  You have 4 unit classifications in this game, and each classification has its own selection of units.  Small, which would obviously be small fighter craft and bombers and others.  Medium, which consists of corvette or Frigate like space craft.  Large, which has cruiser size space craft.  And finally EXTRA LARGE, my favorite, which consists of dreadnaughts, and some other giants of space....  Also base building and capture points,  dont forget that."
76561197989819980,Recommended,249190,31345669,Posted: 24 April,all,dhke,"Ancient Space is a something, that could be called ""2.5D close quarters space strategy"".  Maps are split into sectors linked by warp gates and sectors are again split into multiple, well, for a lack of a better word, areas. It is possible to build structures only in those areas and only at limited locations (typically 2-3 per area, less or more possible). You tend to adopt a ""attack and build strategy"", attacking the next area, building up its defences (structures also help to extend your population cap). This gives the game a relatively leasurely pace, where you usually have time to plan on you next move. Add active pause and you get the deal. This is general flow broken up by some timed missions, where rushing past an area is important. In general, building is only ever to support your fleet. Your carrier(s) are the actual center of the game.If you are into such games, you will like Ancient Space.Your ships have special abilities with a cooldown and using them at the right point (note again: active pause) against the right parts of the enemy armada is quite important.Pro:- closed quarter strategy- takes a more slow approach (minus those missions when it doesn't), but there are still pitched battles.- graphics are decent, the space backdrops and missions are nice.Cons:- The multi-sector approach takes getting used to, especially on those missions where your fleet needs to be split between sectors.- The micromanagement is limited to use of abilties. The rest is more or less melee-range fleet battle, i.e. a mess.- Would you be able to zoom in, you would miss details on the ships. But you cannot zoom in that far.- Fleet customization is limited. The fleet upgrades DO have an effect, but they don't necessarily feel immediately effective.-  The space battles feel a little lackluster.Still, I'd like to see more from this universe, possibly with more customization options, a more extensive campaign with more backstore and exploration."
