,Not Recommended,249190,12212965,"Posted: 23 September, 2014",all,PJthePlayer,"After playing the training scenarios and the first campaign mission (about half an hour) I have to say I am underwhelmed.  Some might say that's too short to draw a conclusion but I have already run into enough disappointment with this game that I've lost interest in it.  I'll break it down into pros and cons:Pros:  The graphics are good and the backdrops look great.  The voice acting is pretty decent as well.  I also thought the soundtrack was strong.  The ship models look good and the moving hardpoints are a nice touch.Cons:  The ""movement"" of the ships, for some reason I cannot quite put my finger on, just does not seem right.  It definitely feels more Sins of a Solar Empire than Homeworld to me.  As a absolutely HUGE Homeworld fan (one of my favorite game series of all time) I was not impressed with this game.  Another big disappointment is the explosions.  In a game like this they should really make the explosions feel powerful and awesome and this game fails tremendously in that reguard.  Large captial ships explode extremely quickly and with a visual and auditory fidelity not up to par with Homeworld 2, a game 11 years its senior.  In Homeworld 2 when a captial ship was destroyed it was EPIC.  In this game it's forgettable.  Weapon effects are largely in the same boat... just underwhelming and almost immediately boring.  Another complaint was that I felt largely underprepared for the first mission following the training scenarios.  The first mission throws several objectives at you and immediately drops you in combat.Overall I'd say that while I respect the intentions of the developer and almost always welcome a sci-fi/space oriented game I just cannot give this game my recommendation.  A few strong aspects are completely overwhelmed by multiple negative ones."
